```markdown
## Webhook Registry System

The webhook handler registry allows for dynamic registration of different webhook types without modifying core application logic.

### Architecture

The registry uses a singleton pattern to maintain a map of webhook types to their respective handlers:

```typescript
// Example of the registry implementation
export class WebhookRegistryService {
  private static instance: WebhookRegistryService;
  private handlers: Map<string, WebhookHandler> = new Map();

  private constructor() {}

  public static getInstance(): WebhookRegistryService {
    if (!WebhookRegistryService.instance) {
      WebhookRegistryService.instance = new WebhookRegistryService();
    }
    return WebhookRegistryService.instance;
  }

  public registerHandler(type: string, handler: WebhookHandler): void {
    if (this.handlers.has(type)) {
      throw new Error(`Handler for webhook type '${type}' already registered`);
    }
    this.handlers.set(type, handler);
  }

  public getHandler(type: string): WebhookHandler | undefined {
    return this.handlers.get(type);
  }
}
```

### Handler Interface

All webhook handlers implement the `WebhookHandler` interface:

```typescript
export interface WebhookHandler {
  readonly type: string;
  handle(payload: unknown): Effect<never, WebhookError, void>;
}
```

### Registration Process

Handlers are registered during application bootstrap:

```typescript
// Example of how handlers are registered
const registry = WebhookRegistryService.getInstance();
registry.registerHandler("reservation", new ReservationWebhookHandler());
registry.registerHandler("payment", new PaymentWebhookHandler());
```

### Processing Flow

1. Webhook request is received at the API endpoint
2. Request is validated for proper signature and format
3. The appropriate handler is retrieved from the registry based on the webhook type
4. The handler processes the webhook payload
5. Response is returned to the caller
```

